<TITLE> Gambia raises salaries by 20 pct after debt relief </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Banjul, Jan 2 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Gambian President Yahya Jammeh announced a 20 percent pay increase for all civil servants on Tuesday, two weeks after multilateral donors approved debt relief for the tiny, impoverished West African country. Jammeh, who seized power in a bloodless military coup nearly 14 years ago, said in his New Year's message that government revenues freed by the debt cancellation would be used on social spending and to retain capacity in the public administration. "These measures include a 20 percent increase in all salaries across the board, with effect from 1 January, 2008," the president said in a speech broadcast on state media. Jammeh said the economy of the former British colony of 1.5 million people, a tiny strip of land surrounded by French speaking Senegal, had grown by about 7 percent in 2007. He pledged to tighten public spending to contain inflation and press ahead with an anti-corruption campaign, "Operation No Compromise". The International Monetary Fund had announced on Dec. 20 that Gambia qualified for the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) initiative, opening the door to a total of $514 million in debt relief
